"Six J., Feller C., Denef K., Ogle S.M., De Moraes Sa J.C., Albrecht A.","Soil organic matter, biota and aggregation in temperate and tropical soils - Effects of no-tillage",2002,"Agronomie","22","7-8",,"755","775",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036868134&partnerID=40&md5=85573d23c8c02537a1a360a87c7bfa11","Department of Agronomy, University of California, Davis, CA 95616, United States; CENA-USP/IRD, Caixa Postal 96, 13400-970 Piracicaba, SP, Brazil; Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO 80523, United States; ICRAF/IRD, PO Box 30677, Nairobi, Kenya","Six, J., Department of Agronomy, University of California, Davis, CA 95616, United States, Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO 80523, United States; Feller, C., CENA-USP/IRD, Caixa Postal 96, 13400-970 Piracicaba, SP, Brazil; Denef, K., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO 80523, United States; Ogle, S.M., Natural Resource Ecology Laboratory, Colorado State University, Fort Collins, CO 80523, United States; De Moraes Sa, J.C., CENA-USP/IRD, Caixa Postal 96, 13400-970 Piracicaba, SP, Brazil; Albrecht, A., ICRAF/IRD, PO Box 30677, Nairobi, Kenya","The long-term stabilization of soil organic matter (SOM) in tropical and temperate regions is mediated by soil biota (e.g. fungi, bacteria, roots and earthworms), soil structure (e.g. aggregation) and their interactions. On average, soil C turnover was twice as fast in tropical compared with temperate regions, but no major differences were observed in SOM quality between the two regions. Probably due to the soil mineralogy dominated by 1:1 clay minerals and oxides in tropical regions, we found a higher aggregate stability, but a lower correlation between C contents and aggregate stability in tropical soils. In addition, a smaller amount of C associated with clay and silt particles was observed in tropical versus temperate soils. In both tropical and temperate soils, a general increase in C levels (≈ 325 ± 113 kg C·ha-1·yr-1) was observed under no-tillage compared with conventional tillage. On average, in temperate soils under no-tillage, compared with conventional tillage, CH4 uptake (≈ 0.42 ± 0.10 kg C-CH4·ha-1·yr-1) increased and N2O emissions increased (≈ 1.95 ± 0.45 kg N-N2O·ha-1·yr-1). These increased N20 emissions lead to a negative global warming potential when expressed on a CO2 equivalent basis.","Aggregation; N2O emissions; Soil carbon; Temperate and tropical soil; Tillage","soil aggregate; soil biota; soil organic matter; soil structure; tillage; Bacteria (microorganisms); cellular organisms; Fungi; Pheretima sieboldi",,,,,,"Albrecht, A., Rangon, L., Barret, P., Effets de la matière organique sur la stabilité structurale et la détachabilité d'un vertisol et d'un ferrisol (Martinique) (1992) Cah. Orstom. Ser. Pedol., 27, pp. 121-133; Alvarez, R., Russo, M.E., Prystupa, P., Scheiner, J.D., Blotta, L., Soil carbon pools under conventional and no-tillage systems in the Argentine Rolling Pampa (1998) Agron. J., 90, pp. 138-143; Amado, T.J.C., Mielniczuk, J., Fernandes, S.B.V., Potencial de culturas de cobertura em acumular carbono e nitrogenio no solo no plantio direto e a melhoria da qualidade ambiental (2001) R. Bras. Ci. Solo, 25, pp. 189-197; Amelung, W., Zech, W., Zhang, X., Follett, R.F., Tiessen, H., Knox, E., Flach, K.W., Carbon nitrogen, and sulfur pools in particle-size fractions as influenced by climate (1998) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 62, pp. 172-181; Angers, D.A., Giroux, M., Recently deposited organic matter in soil water-stable aggregates (1996) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 60, pp. 1547-1551; Angers, D.A., Mehuys, G.R., Barley and alfalfa cropping effects on carbohydrate contents of a clay soil and its size fractions (1990) Soil Biol. Biochem., 22, pp. 285-288; Angers, D.A., N'Dayegamiye, A., Effects of manure application on carbon, nitrogen, and carbohydrate contents of a 